While Milwaukee means a lot of things to a lot of people, both good and bad, this is still a place that many of us call home. Some of us have been here our whole life and others have just arrived. I think my favorite thing about this city (besides it’s natural beauty) is the fact that we are not defined by one thing, one school, one company or one mindset, we are a collection of 600,000 of the most talented, energized (& sometimes seasonally depressed) people in this country. While our city continues to scrape by with minimal support from the state government, Milwaukee is continuing to thrive and push forward on its own. I think my favorite part about calling this place home is that the best is yet to come. Milwaukee’s next chapter is still being written and we, the people have the power to make it what we want. From new housing and new transit lines to new cultural institutions and community amenities we are reimagining this city from the ground up. For every negative story out there, there is a positive one. So be the change you want to see in this city and let’s make Milwaukee the best city in America. (& I’ll continue to capture it) 
.
.

We have to do better as a community and find ways to come together to stop the violence - too many of our loved ones are being affected by these senseless acts that jeopardize everything we’ve been building together as a community. I send my condolences to the fallen officers friends, family and colleagues.
.

Side note - those parking lots are such a waste of prime real estate. That land has so much more potential than being used for parking for just 12 weekends throughout the summer months. We could easily add in some mixed use buildings with some parking structures to accommodate cars but I think we could go even further. It’s about time we can quit the politics and give the metro area a RTA that can efficiently connect people to the city and it’s suburbs. Imagine a train station outside the Summerfest grounds (think of something like Denver’s Union Station) with lines running out to the burbs right outside Summerfests main gate. Then imagine a dense urban mixed use neighborhood being build out around it connecting the @historicthirdward to the @summerfest grounds. The potential is there, but do we have the drive to make it happen? 🤔
.

While Juneteenth might be the newest federal holiday, Milwaukee has had one of the longest running Juneteenth celebrations in the country - 52 years and counting. What the “FAQ” Is Hoanchella? 🤔 

So glad you asked!👇

Q: Why should I purchase a VIP experience?
A: We are creating a multi-sensory extravaganza that pushes the boundaries of entertainment, offering an unforgettable experience for attendees. As a VIP, you get to be front row and experience this unique spectacle LIVE while we position Milwaukee as a beacon of innovation and creativity.

Q: HOW ARE DONATIONS USED?
A: The monies raised from the HOANCHELLA fundraising event will go towards installing 2,500 of computer-controlled LED lights to illuminate the Hoan Bridge on the east side of the bridge. A portion of the funds will also be put into a reserve fund to provide for regular bridge maintenance up to 10 years for both sides.

Q: IS MY GIFT/Ticket TAX DEDUCTIBLE?
A: Light the Hoan, Inc. is a 501(c)(3) organization and donations to it are tax deductible to the extent allowed by law.

Q: If I have a boat but do not want to purchase a VIP Boat Slip Experience, can I still attend?
A: Absolutely! We hope you will join us for music during Happy Hour at Lakeshore State Park from 4pm-6:30pm. We do ask that all the boats who are part of the VIP experience be guided first and kept together as we head up the river. We have put a lot of coordination into this guided experience with the Milwaukee Police and Fire Department for everyone’s safely. Please consider donating a bulb to support our fundraising efforts at www.lightthehoan.com.

Q: Can we watch the light show and fireworks from our boats?
A: Of course, the Milwaukee River is open for everyone to enjoy! Please note that The Miss Wisconsin and VIP Boats will have right of way when we approach the Hoan Bridge for the light show set with DJ Shawna. The entire experience is being shot from multiple angels and the positioning of boats is being coordinated. You are welcome to find a spot after we have positioned ourselves. Please consider donating a bulb to support our fundraising efforts at www.lightthehoan.com.

Please visit www.lightthehoan.com for more FAQ’s and info!

Big days today and tomorrow as @wisdot will be holding meetings regarding the future of I-794 through downtown. Urban freeways radically reshaped our cities, destroying dense neighborhoods, divided our communities and are shown to increase dependence on cars. Milwaukee - a pioneer in urban freeway removal, has the ability to reimagine the city once again. Tearing down the Park East freeway reconnected our neighborhoods, lead to the construction of @fiservforum and the @deerdistrict and will soon be home to the @milwaukeepublicmuseum. We have the opportunity to act boldly once again and reconnect the @historicthirdward and @mkedowntown. While both neighborhoods are thriving, there exists an opportunity to compound that momentum. I encourage you to attend and let your voice be heard. The first meeting is tonight at the Milwaukee Marriott Downtown - from 4-7 and the second is tomorrow at St Thomas More High School from 4-7.
.

I’m sure you’ve seen the news now that the @mlb and our beloved @brewers in talks to extend their lease at American Family Field with the stipulation that significant investment is made to upgrade the facility. The Wisconsin Legislator has come up with a plan (to the tune of $700 million) to keep the team in town and bring the stadium up to league standards. With significant funding expected to come from the city, the mayor is pushing the Brewers to pursue development on at least a part of their parking lots. The Brewers president of business operations has expressed resistance to anything that would infringe on the stadium's "tailgating culture.”
.
With that being said, I went out last night to shoot the stadium which is still  a work of art and a huge asset to the community. I also made it a point to include as many of the 12,000+ parking spaces as I could. We have such a huge opportunity to create another stadium district (Beer District) similar to the Deer District downtown. Look at Atlanta’s @batteryatl or @bpvstl for examples in the MLB.
.
If I had the ability, I’d build out the lots to the east of Brewers Boulevard while maintaining the lots immediately adjacent to the stadium. I’d create a mixed use neighborhood with office space, retail, hotels and housing flanking both sides of the Menomonee River with an eventual transit connection to downtown and the western suburbs. There’s no reason we can’t accommodate the Brewers renowned tailgating culture and a thriving mixed use ballpark village that contributes to the city’s tax base. What are your thoughts on creating a Ballpark District near @amfamfield ?
.

It’s always interesting seeing what publications have to say about Milwaukee when they write about it. Here is what @cntraveler had to say about MKE - “Long considered nearby Chicago’s little sibling, Milwaukee has finally come into its own by growing amongst younger people for its affordability over the Second City, allowing people to buy homes and rent better apartments. Not to mention the growing restaurant scene, new infrastructure increasing walkability, and enough city amenities for the Midwest gem to truly feel desirable—it’s no longer just a small town. And with so many local colleges and a venerated art museum, there is strong curiosity and willingness to embrace the new.”
.
I think my favorite part of the whole bit is the “willingness to embrace the new.” I feel like Milwaukee used to be a city that was stuck in its own way, scared to make the big decisions that help define a place. I’m not sure when that mentality shifted - maybe it was when the Milwaukee Art Museum was built, maybe it’s when the city tore out the park east freeway but those decisions have compounded over the years and have helped create the beautiful city you see here. In the years that followed we’ve seen huge companies and developers double down on downtown. The Bucks built Fiserv Forum, towers continue to rise around the city - it’s been a ton of fun to watch. With that being said, we have the opportunity to continue to embrace the change - huge decisions lie ahead of us in the coming years with the future of 794 and Am Fam Field and the potential sitting there in Brewers parking lots. Big decisions like this aren’t easy but can change a trajectory of a city from being average to being great. It’s going to be cool to see how the dust settles on these big ideas and see what @cntraveler has to say in another 10 years.
.
#milwaukee
